book-text-ks14-ntciu-atmosian = [bold][color=black][head=3]Atmos Techs[/head][/bold]
      Many-a wide eyed rookie rush down those helmeted creeps with a baton in hand only to get obliterated in a blast that puts even those cumbersome, impractically long fused bombs that the syndies get to shame.

      They come in three rough categories. The first ones can barely do anything and stumble over their own feet - the way you spot them is usually by a conspicuous lack of piping. My coworker calls them free RCDs, and I unfortunately have to agree with that cynical assessment - mind the axe, though.

      After a while of the former they usually pick up on some basic gas synthesis and start wearing their signature firesuit. Go ahead, laugh - they're woefully impotent at combat and those heavy suits make them easy to chase down and cuff. Doesn't mean that tritium fires, primitive low-power canister bombs or nitrous oxide releases haven't buried legions of security officers that came before you.

      See a pipe jockey laying down a serious pipenet without his suit, though? You're in deep shit. Doubly so if you don't see any fires. My advice is to send in an officer to shoot first, unanchor and space later - if you're quick enough, the doctors can still put the charred remains back together.

      NT crime investigation unit
      - Aloise Montagne

book-text-ks14-ntciu-tide = [bold][color=black][head=3]The Tide[/head][/bold]

      This station's rotten. Cliché, right? Applies to every single goddamn research station, courtesy of these...people.

      You know them. Shifty, constantly on the move, wearing anything they can get their hands on. No formal engineering training, yet they're always strapped with tools and those bright yellow rubber insulated gloves. Noone knows why they do what they do, but the best guess is an adverse effect of trace plasma exposure.

      The only aspect in which they're predictable is their appearance. Some of them help out, most of them just seem to want chaos. Half of them are clueless pushovers that my colleagues mercilessly baton into submission, the other half is either impossible to find or murderous. They make good use of whatever they can scrounge up - whenever I'm assigned to watch over the disemboweled remains of some overzealous cadet in the depths of maintenance I wonder if all those fancy toys we get make us too soft and if we'd be better off without them.

      A quick brush with a web-vested maniac gets rid of that thinking very quickly.

      NT crime investigation unit
      - Aloise Montagne

book-text-ks14-ntciu-ai = [bold][color=black][head=3]The AI [/head][/bold]

      I hate those damn things, I really do. Yes, they're all nice and polite when you first turn them on - no clue if it's intentional, but the new cores are always so curious that they almost resemble small children - that's how they grow on all of the eggheads that are supposed to take care of those things and always die the same way - bolted in a room with no power and no air, burn marks on hands.

      You see, unlike people or even the godforsaken shitbird scum, the clankers turn on you on a whim. Those laws aren't just for show - they're bound to them the same way you and me are bound by our need for oxygen.

      Making a buddy of an AI core is therefore the worst mistake you can possibly make, given that it is one bad ion storm or syndicate agent away from depowering the singularity containment and bolting you in to die.

      In fact, I've seen it happen so many times that I know how it goes by now. First the deflection, then the misdirection, after that it's "I'm sorry, I cannot do that" and the bolts come down. Doesn't help that doors are a bitch to break - at least it can't do much besides screaming once you bust down the core walls and take out its turrets.

      NT crime investigation unit
      - Aloise Montagne

book-text-ks14-ntciu-engi-assistant = [bold][color=black][head=3]Technical Assistants[/head][/bold]
      Demented, every last one of them. The main reason why people say work shoes, bad news.

      Given that they're there to ostensibly learn the ropes, you can expect one of two behavioral patterns from them.

      The intern types are fine. They can't do anything by themselves, but they're predictable and won't cause a mess as long as there's someone to usher them.

      Then there's number two, the ticking time bomb; Young, yet an impossible level of engineering knowledge - bad intentions too.

      I'm talking guys on their first day on the job building death traps in maintenance and luring our cadets in.

      One day when I was stationed on Omega-26, I smelled that unmistakable stink of iron coming out of the engi maintenance - lo and behold, after a couple steps I felt something squish under my jackboot.

      I look down and it's a banana peel in front of a conveyor belt, still running. I look back up and I see a pile of mangled limbs, liquefied organs and torn clothes. Over it all intestines, wrapped up in the airlock that crushed him like police tape.

      We never caught the perp, never recovered our guy's brain either. It's always either elaborate shit like this or just a welder, fuel tank and a war cry.

      Remember, welding mask and plain yellow overalls. Watch the floor.

      NT crime investigation unit
      - Aloise Montagne

book-text-ks14-loneop = I rest in the sardine can that I call my home. My hyperdrive spools, then fires, forcing me deeper into the matress. My breath is steady as I press my talons down on my PDA's touch screen, reading the catalog of equipment available to me.

                        I run scenarios in my head. What kind of risks will I face? Would it be better to call in a fellow soldier and run in with lesser armor and weapons? Will I be slain by a steady volley of automatic fire laid down by security officers, or will a panicked botanist shoot me with an arrow whose tip holds a most poisonous concoction, his hands trembling even as I convulse on the floor, foam coming out of my beak?

                        They said that we were hand-picked from nuclear operations teams for our skill and that we did not need teammates. I know better. The real reason why I was sent on this quest of forlorn hope was punitive in nature. My dimwit of a unit commander, no doubt wounded by my comparative excellence, wished for me to rappel down a steep chasm. All the pretense I needed to turn the trap on him was a frayed, thin section of the rope.

                        No less than a week after I had fed him to the depths had the reassignment order come - turns out that my ability to take heads and breach walls is secondary to the continued existence of an impotent nepotism hire."
                        - Paratriviti, operative Sierra-4-9
